<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25077g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25077g">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25077g"> 77(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> not recognise him / &mdash; mention him / cut &mdash;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Thus there is a well-marked preponderance indicating that ceremonial avoidance by the husband is in some way connected with his living with his wife&apos;s family, and vice versa as to the wife and the husband&apos;s family. The reason of this connection &lsquo;readily presents itself, inasmuch as the ceremony of <mark>not speaking to and pretending not to see</mark> some well-known person close by, is familiar enough to ourselves in the social rite which we call &ldquo;<mark>cutting</mark>.&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> We have only to say that they <mark>do not recognise</mark> their son-in-law, and we shall have condensed the whole proceeding into a single word. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 122-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14046c" href="c14all.htm#c14046c">VI.C.14:046(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
